Overview

This experiment demonstrates the fundamentals of network communication using Python sockets.
We build a simple system where a client sends a message to a server, and the server responds back.

This forms the foundation of system design, as almost all distributed systems rely on client-server communication.

Objectives
Understand how client-server architecture works
Learn socket programming in Python
Establish communication using TCP protocol
Send and receive data between systems
Get introduced to network ports and connections
Requirements
Software
Python 3.x installed
Any code editor (VS Code / PyCharm / Notepad++)
Terminal or Command Prompt
Libraries Used
Built-in Python library:
socket
threading (optional for multi-client)

No external installations required

How to Run
Step 1: Start Server
python server.py
Step 2: Start Client (in another terminal)
python client.py
Workflow
Server starts and listens on a specific port (5000)
Client connects using IP address + port
Client sends a message
Server receives and processes it
Server sends a response back
Connection is closed
Internal Working
Key Concepts
1. Socket

A socket is an endpoint for communication between two machines.

socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)
AF_INET → IPv4
SOCK_STREAM → TCP protocol
2. Server Side
bind() → Assigns IP and port
listen() → Waits for incoming connections
accept() → Accepts client connection
server.bind(("localhost", 5000))
server.listen(1)
client_socket, addr = server.accept()
3. Client Side
connect() → Connects to server
client.connect(("localhost", 5000))
4. Data Transmission
Data is sent in bytes, not strings
Hence we use:
.encode()   # string → bytes
.decode()   # bytes → string
5. Communication Flow
Client  -------->  Server
        message

Server  -------->  Client
        response
What You Will Learn

By completing this experiment, you will:

Understand how the internet works at a basic level
Learn TCP communication
Understand request-response model
Get clarity on ports, IPs, sockets
Build foundation for:

REST APIs
Microservices
Distributed systems
Chat applications
Extensions (Optional)

Try enhancing your project:

Echo server (send back same message)
Continuous communication using loops
Handle multiple clients using threads
Build a simple chat system
Common Errors
Error	Cause	Fix
Address already in use	Port occupied	Change port
Connection refused	Server not running	Start server first
Program stuck	Waiting for input	Expected behavior
Real-World Relevance

This experiment is the base of:

Web servers (like Apache, Nginx)
Messaging apps (WhatsApp, Telegram)
Distributed systems
APIs and microservices
Conclusion

This experiment introduces the core building block of system design — communication between systems.

Mastering this ensures you can understand how real-world scalable systems operate internally.